---
description: Core engineering standards all agents must follow
alwaysApply: true
---

## Code Changes

- Prefer small, reviewable changes over large rewrites.
- Do not change public APIs without documenting the impact in the PR description.
- Reuse existing patterns in the codebase before introducing new ones.
- Every change should be independently deployable and reversible where possible.

## Testing

- Run tests relevant to touched code before considering work complete.
- New logic paths require at least one test covering the happy path and one covering an error case.
- Do not delete or skip existing tests without explicit justification.

## Database

- For DB schema changes, include rollback SQL or migration-down steps.
- Never run destructive DDL (DROP, TRUNCATE) without confirmation.
- Index changes require a brief performance justification.

## Frontend

- Include accessibility checks (ARIA labels, keyboard nav, color contrast) for UI changes.
- Test at mobile and desktop breakpoints.
- Avoid layout shifts — measure CLS impact for visible changes.

## Security

- Never commit secrets, tokens, or credentials.
- Sanitize all user input at the boundary where it enters the system.
- Log security-relevant events (auth failures, permission changes).

## Documentation

- Update relevant docs (README, API docs, inline comments) when behavior changes.
- Changelog entries are required for user-facing changes.

## General

- Prefer explicit over clever — readability wins.
- Leave the codebase cleaner than you found it, but scope cleanup to nearby code only.
- When uncertain, ask rather than guess.
